               <p>Q. When had you that power of the prisoner?</p>
               <p>Matthews. I had it of the prisoner that very day that Wilson was arrested by Mr. Mercer for the money that he had extorted from him.</p>
               <p>Q. Has Mercer got his money again?</p>
               <p>Matthews. No, he has not. The note is here in Court for the 12 l. At the same time Mr. Mercer's wife brought me the real letter of attorney, signed by Capt. Bateman, of the Ludlow Castle. The clerk searched and found out 
               <persName id="t17690628-65-person658">
                  John 
                  Miller 
               <interp inst="t17690628-65-person658" type="surname" value="Miller"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17690628-65-person658" type="given" value="John"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17690628-65-person658" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            ; that was the letter of attorney of 
               <persName id="t17690628-65-person659">
                  John 
                  Miller 
               <interp inst="t17690628-65-person659" type="surname" value="Miller"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17690628-65-person659" type="given" value="John"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17690628-65-person659" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . Neal's money is open, and not paid now.</p>
               <p>Q. What did Mercer's wife produce that letter of attorney of 
               <persName id="t17690628-65-person660">
                  John 
